The architects saw in - the office also includes a kindergarten
The Avriopoint office building in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
But who would expect a mini kindergarten here, with everything involved: colorful walls, creative furniture, a lot of toys and even a mini playground on the outdoor terrace.
This kindergarten has been available to the employees of Arch.Design since last year.
The design and architectural office Arch.Design, from whose ateliers a whole series of renowned Brno buildings originated, counted from the first designs for the new building Avriopoint on the premises for its company’s mini-children’s garden.
In a wise outlook, because most of its 90 employees are in the baby boom age and the company is focused on the project architects to return to their workplace as soon as possible.
Along with the opportunity to work shortened, the kindergarten is another bonus that Arch.Design has to offer its employees in the concept of its social program.
This makes it easier for civil engineers to combine their demanding profession and childcare.
The Minikindergarten is an original idea of the employees of Arch.Design and with the support of the management, they managed to win grants from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs for their project.
The operational kindergarten is financed by the Operational Programme Human Resources and Employment Policy from the European Social Fund and the state budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to this funding (subsidies of 2.8 million CZK) the necessary facilities and equipment were purchased and for a period of 2 years qualified personnel and operation was provided.
After the funding is exhausted (2 years), the company Arch.Design is obliged to continue operating the Minikindergarten 3 more years at its own expense.
The preparation of this project took a whole year, with the company Economy Rating providing active assistance in the processing of the application.
To the children is cared for full-time qualified staff - a nurse and a kindergarten teacher, the kindergarten can attend children without age restrictions, although most of them are over three years old.
And since this is a mini kindergarten, only 5 children can be present at the same time, but several children alternate over the day.
The kindergarten operation is flexibly tailored to the needs of the parents, the children of all employees have the same rights in terms of the use of the kindergarten - regardless of the company hierarchy and their respective position.
Although it is an individual education and care, the program content in the mini kindergarten is nevertheless comparable to the framework program of preschool education.
The children are not only playing here, above all, they are offered excellent lessons - from basic insights to preschool lessons, besides they also learn English.
The classroom is equipped not only with toys and creative games, but also with a computer available to the children.
What’s more – the presence of young children in the company contributes to a friendly and positive company environment.
Parents can take a look at the children at any time and thus eliminate the stress of late picking up the children from a distant kindergarten.
Parents use their working hours more productively.
No wonder that there are also natural and loyal employer-employee relationships.
Arch.Design thus ranked among the Czech companies that offer significant benefits in the recruitment of new employees, which are family-friendly and through such programs strengthen their human resources marketing.
A bone house fascinates even after 100 years.
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric oak, the stairs like the backbone of a dinosaur, and the balconies are ripped fish walls.
This is the Casa Batlló of the Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
From the local inhabitants, the house, with its organic shapes, received the nickname "Bone House".
Organic shapes, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, bricks and mosaics, the shell-like facades and ubiquitous soft lines, all of these are typical features of the youth style of Antonio Gaudi.
The façade of the house plays with dreamy lines, tender colors and textures that remind us of nature and living creatures.
Only with a closer look is it noticed that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm and thoughtful order.
At night, the entire facade looks even more plastic, dramatic, and the special lighting enhances the gloss of the colors.
The same swinging lines and swollen shapes also dominate the interior of the house.
Wave-shaped wood copies the window frames, bars, ornamental elements of doors, and even glove holes and bars.
The Batlló House in the Eixample district on the bustling shopping street Passeig de Grácia No. 43 was created by the reconstruction of a house from 1877, which was carried out by the architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrial Josep Batlló, initially insisted on the demolition of the old and the construction of a completely new building, but eventually agreed to Gaudí’s idea of an unusual and also cheaper reconstruction.
The Casa Batlló was not designed by Antoni Gaudí.
He worked with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
It was on his drawing board that the decorations for the reality owner’s representative apartment were created, and the use of mosaics on the façade was also his idea.
However, many other artists and artists also worked on the design of the façade.
The joint work on the designs for the Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful collaboration between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaudí's House Casa Milá in Park Güell, which also houses other works by Antoni Gaudí.
Shortly after its completion, the house received its organic shapes from the local inhabitants due to the nickname "Bone House".
Others, in turn, called it the special window opening mechanism due to the "climbing house".
It is also said that at the top of the building is depicted the sword of St. George, the patron of Catalonia.
But other sculptural elements also symbolize hidden religious motives.
Gaudí designed for the house a central heating system unique to the time with ventilation channels and typical fireplaces.
Somewhat strange is her 45-degree inclination already.
In his creation, Gaudí consistently ignored all the construction regulations of the time and was by no means misled by them.
Before the construction began, he obtained the appropriate building permission from the city, but the information he made about the planned reconstruction was so vague that two years later the town fathers were so shocked by the result of the completion that they demanded remedy.
The councillors also encountered, among other things, that the building with its pillars even entered the public sidewalk.
However, there were no changes, quite the opposite – just fifteen days after the district’s request in this regard, Josep Batlló submitted a request for permission to rent the two highest floors of the house – and it was promptly granted to him.
The owner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery on the 2nd floor there was a social salon, on the 3rd floor were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The entire six-story building runs through a staircase up to the roof terrace.
Due to the fundamental elements of the reconstruction, all straight angles and straight lines were removed and replaced by curved and curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with a modern concept of interconnecting spaces.
The social part can be fully connected through the opening of the salon doors and so a larger society could chat comfortably without having to give up some intimacy in more confidential conversations.
In addition to a new façade, the house received a rather unusual roof and two more floors through Gaudi's reconstruction.
Also impressive is Gaudí's play with the light as well as the blue and white glazed tiles with which the courtyard is dressed and the light courtyards.
The game of these two colors gives all floors of the house a maximum level of light.
In doing so, he simply used the principle that white reflects light better than dark colors, which, on the contrary, absorb sunlight.
The Casa Batlló, which was listed on the UNESCO World Heritage List in 2005, is now accessible to anyone.
On the first floor, the most spacious and magnificent apartment is made accessible to the public.
The homeowners decided to take this step only in the year and this on the occasion of the 150th birthday of the famous creator.
When it was found that this was a fairly profitable business, the visits were kept, and they were also extended to other common and the rooftop spaces, including the rooftop terrace.
However, the price for visiting the building temple is not a piece of paper, it is 16.50 euros, students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist passports get a 20% discount.
This amount exceeds the entrance prices to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
Anyone who wants to know the real atmosphere of the house with its dragon towers should try to make friendship with one of the residents of the house and visit him at home.
