More and more parents want human surveillance devices to keep children under control
The fear of their own children is growing and so more and more parents are considering monitoring them via GPS.
The system, which was originally invented for the search for cars, can identify people as well, which would be useful in such cases as recently with the traceless disappearance of the nine-year-old Anička Janatková.
The device is currently about the size of a cigarette box but soon it is not likely to be larger than a wristwatch.
Many people are scared and frightened by the case of the missing Anička and are looking for ways and means to better protect their children.
Even at the cost of compromising their privacy.
“We are trying to tell everyone that this is not about spying around, but an effective way to reduce the likelihood of a tragedy,” says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of GPS localization devices on the Czech market.
“I admit that there can be misuse of such devices in individual cases, for example, if you put them in someone’s pocket without them knowing, but we haven’t recorded such a case so far.”
“Most customers really buy it for safety reasons,” Pilin adds.
In his opinion, however, the child should always know what purpose the "box" serves and how to use it in an emergency.
However, child psychologist Dana Bočková points out that if a child doesn’t like to wear such a thing, it simply gets rid of it.
“Even very young children show great creativity when it comes to deliberately losing certain things if they don’t want to be controlled.”
"The phones initially raised great expectations among parents, but they can be turned off as easily as these new surveillance devices," says Ms. Bočková.
In their opinion, it is also controversial whether such a facility actually helps in the event of an attack.
“In planned abductions, the kidnapper practically always checks whether the child has any electronics with him that could be used to locate him.”
“Today it is the phone.”
“If such surveillance devices were more widely used, they would also look for them, as their sales would be accompanied by massive advertising.”
“In these cases, the police criminals are always one step ahead,” says the psychologist.
