A longer index finger than a ring finger means a lower risk of developing cancer
Men whose index finger is longer than the ring finger are obviously at a lower risk of developing prostate cancer.
This is the surprising result of a study published on Wednesday in the British Journal of Cancer.
This is related to the level of the male hormone testosterone.
“Our results show that the relative length of the fingers can serve as a simple test for the risk of prostate cancer, especially in men up to sixty,” said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Cancer Research Institute at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should definitely undergo a prostate cancer test, especially if there are genetic risks or other risk factors, such as family health stresses, Ms. Eeles added.
Between 1994 and 2009, she and her colleagues in the UK followed more than 1,500 patients with prostate cancer, but also 3,000 healthy men.
In more than half of the study participants, the right hand’s index finger was shorter than the ring finger.
For these men, the likelihood of prostate cancer was the same as for 19 percent of those men whose ring and index fingers were the same length.
For men whose index finger was longer than the ring finger, however, this risk decreased by 33 percent, and for men up to sixty even by 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two mentioned fingers, which are already formed in prenatal age, obviously reflects the different levels of sex hormones to which the child was exposed in the womb.
Less testosterone is equivalent to a longer index finger.
Previous research has shown that testosterone accelerates the growth of prostate cancer.
Václav Pačes, a leading Czech geneticist and former chairman of the Academy of Sciences, told ČTK that he was flightly aware of this study, yet he does not think the relationship between finger length and cancer risk has been "fully proven" so far.
