The democracy movement in Latin America is becoming stronger, as is the support for private companies.
Crime is a bigger problem than unemployment.
In many parts of the region, the influence of Brazil is greater than that of the United States.
These findings came from the Latinobarometer survey, conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively in The Economist.
This survey has been conducted regularly since 1995 and thus shows the change of opinion in this region.
Two facts are especially highlighted in this year’s survey of September and October.
The Good Mood in Latin America
And secondly, the growing interest in democracy and its key institutions.
In many countries on the South American Pacific coast, the democratic movement has grown sharply (see Table 1).
In Peru, for example, where the economy has grown by about 6% annually since 2002, the number of Democracy supporters has increased from 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
Also in Mexico, where the economy has recovered since the strong recession last year, such a trend is visible.
But only half of respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the most populous countries in the region, are convinced Democrats, lowering the regional average (see chart 2).
Approximately 44% of respondents stated that they are satisfied with the democratic practice of their country.This is as many as last year, but 25% more than in 2001 (Chart 3).
Approximately 34% trust their country’s Congress and 45% their government. Both figures are the same as last year, but show a significant increase compared to 2003 (17% and 24% respectively).
A decade ago, Latin America’s economic crises undermined efforts for more democracy.
That this continued during the global economic crisis may be due to the fact that Latin American countries experienced only a short period of recession and recovered rapidly.
In addition, the poor were captured by a stronger social network.
(According to reports from the UN Economic Commission for Latin America this week, the poverty rate in Latin America rose only slightly in 2009 and has fallen by 32% again this year.)
However, there are significant differences between countries (see diagram 4).
Brazil’s strong economy and the popularity of the departing President Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva are reflected in a widespread progressive thinking.
In Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more noticeable and violent crimes increased, this is less the case.
It is only the second time since the start of the survey that many respondents in Latin America see crime in their country as a bigger problem than unemployment (see Chart 5).
Approximately 31% say that either they themselves or a family member have been victims of a crime in the past year, but compared to 38% in the past year, the figures have dropped, reaching the lowest level since 1995.
The increasing economic performance is reflected in the stronger support for the private and market economies: approximately 71% of respondents across regions said that the private sector is essential for development, compared with 56% in 2007 (see chart 6).
Approximately 58% stated that only the market economy can bring progress to their country, compared to 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela haveined this view (and 80% are for a private sector), despite their leftist president, Hugo Chávez, nationalizing many private companies.
Brazil has the largest weight in the region, according to 19% of respondents (18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, unchanged since last year) and Venezuela (9% compared to 11% last year).
Respondents in Mexico and most Central American countries, on the other hand, see the U.S. as the most influential country, with this role being taken over by Venezuela in the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
A Electoral Trap
No one expected the November 28 elections in Haiti to be perfect.
But the facts far surpassed the fears of the voters who rushed to help the crushed country.
