The discovery of an alien bacterial species that can live from arsenic, among others, opens up new possibilities for new life forms on Earth and elsewhere.
Although scientists discovered this unusual bacterium here on Earth, they believe it is a sign that life is possible without the elements previously considered vital.
“This organism has two possibilities.”
It needs either phosphorus or arsenic to grow.
“That makes it something very special, even though it’s almost a kind of ‘foreign’ form of life,” said Paul C.W. Davies of Arizona State University and co-author of the report, which appears in the online issue of the journal Science on Thursday.
So far, six main elements have been considered vital - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
But as the scientists found out, the bacterium in California’s Mono Lake grows even further when it replaces phosphorus with arsenic.
“You wonder what else is possible,” said Ariel D. Anbar, co-author of the report from Arizona State University.
The discovery is an important step in the search for extraterrestrial life as scientists have to identify life and its forms, Anbar said.
The study examines microbes found on Earth.
The announcement of a press conference, in which no details were announced about the discovery, gave rise to widespread speculation on the Internet that the report might be about the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
This is not the case.
The discovery “shows that organisms in other planetary systems can trigger biochemical processes with the help of other elements and that the ‘standard elements’ that we believe are absolutely vital are not necessarily fixed,” said Charles Cockell, a professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute at the Open University of Milton Keynes in the UK.
Cockel was not part of the research team.
"This work is a novelty because it shows that in fundamental biochemical processes and structures one element can be replaced by another," Cockell added.
This discovery was not accidental.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA’s Astrobiology Institute, who led the study, chose the Mono Lake due to its high arsenic content.
Since arsenic and phosphorus are chemically identical, she assumed that microbes exposed to both could potentially replace one element with the other.
"The toxicity of arsenic is mainly due to its chemical similarity to phosphorus."
"This makes it difficult for organisms to distinguish one element from the other."
“But the difference is so great that arsenic acts differently than phosphorus. it enters our biochemical system, where it smells almost everything,” Anbar explains.
The researchers exposed the bacterium GFAJ-1 to rising arsenic concentrations.
Although the microbe grows better in phosphorus, the fact that it can also survive in arsenic shows that an arsenic-based life form can occur naturally, either on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
According to Jamie S. Foster, a professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, the idea that phosphorus can be replaced by arsenic is not new.
Arsenic was more common in the early Earth years, she says, so science has assumed that early life forms used it.
"This gives reason to believe that life may have evolved differently than it did in the early Earth Age," said Forster, who was not a member of Wolfe-Simons research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Ministry of Energy and the National Health Agency.
