Can courtesy unite the separating?
After a campaign of blasphemy and negativity, little courtesy broke out in Washington this week.
Is it the premise of a real two-party cooperation or a moment of illusion before you quickly return to the struggle of the parties in the capital?
Tuesday’s meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders did not bring a breakthrough in the major issues to be addressed during the so-called “lame duck session,” the session at the end of a term in which no decisions are made.
After all that is heard, it was neither a polite discussion between two different sides nor a consideration of their shared responsibility to rule, but rather an empty episode of a partial point-gathering.
The president’s deficit committee’s public meeting on Wednesday was also civilized, despite the political differences that still exist between the members.
It seems to be clear that close interaction over a period of months creates mutual respect, masking the ideological gap that continues to separate the members from each other.
This is hardly enough to say that a new era of cooperation has begun.
Both sides are now in a test phase – in which one requires from the other signs of cooperation and compromise, while one tries to weigh the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters after a new party warfare.
Therefore, the meeting on Tuesday itself and its assessment by the participants were limited to a minimum of claims or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too large and too deep to expect a rapid change in the atmosphere that has prevailed over the past two years.
Whether it’s about taxes, donations, health care or welfare, the two sides are miles apart.
Lastly, in the November elections, Washington voted mildly, at least for a short time.
“No question, the tone has changed,” said Pete Wehner, an official spokesman for the Bush administration who is now working for the Ethics and Public Policy Center.
This is inevitable after the elections.
Elections arouse party passions that die away again.
And that is good.”
On some issues, especially those on the agenda of the “lame duck session,” Republicans and Democrats have hardly any other choice but to find a solution.”
Bush’s tax cuts end at the end of the year, and nobody supports that.
Both sides want to find a way to get some or all of them, whether temporarily or permanently.
Similarly, a compromise on increased unemployment benefits is to be expected, though only because Republicans cannot afford to believe favored tax cuts for the rich while refusing to support unemployed workers.
After Tuesday’s meeting in the White House, optimism has risen that one can agree on these issues during the “lame duck session” and at the same time also ratify the New START treaty.
But William Glaston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on the urgent issues of the “lame duck session” doesn’t necessarily lead to permanent cooperation between the parties when the new 112th Congress is convened in January.
Instead, he says, a phase of disagreement is more likely, even inevitable.
“Once the things that need to be done are done, this short-term psychology will turn into confrontation,” he said.
Wehner is also skeptical — and this skepticism is shared by many — that courtesy leads to true cooperation.
"I see a lot of what is happening from today to 2012 as a pre-fight, or shadow boxes, for the main event of 2012," he said.
The reasons for this have much to do with the creation of the new Republican majority in the White House and the Tea Party voters who served their formation.
No matter how concerned the Republican leaders are about playing too high poker, they know that they must try to keep their promises of cutting government spending and dismantling health care reform.
These partisan lines are already evident in the first reactions to the recommendations of the Deficit Commission, which include a tax reform and the raising of some taxes as well as the raising of the retirement age and the reduction of government spending.
Vice Presidents Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken on one of the most difficult jobs in Washington and, in their own opinion, have pushed so hard to put the issue of deficit on the public agenda that they can no longer be ignored.
But they need 14 of the 18 votes in the commission to make their plan an official recommendation and they are struggling to get close to that number.
The biggest resistance is found in the elected representatives of the panel, since in financial matters, at least today, there is little margin or little sympathy for compromise.
Galston predicts two phases in the struggle between the White House and the Republicans in Congress.
The first struggle will take place next year in the form of party clashes, as Republicans challenge Obama in terms of state budget, taxes, and the health system, followed later by a phase of wider bilateral cooperation.
What will lead to this change?
The public opinion.
It is proven that, despite the partiality of the current election, the majority of Americans still want the two parties to work together.
If confrontation leads to an impasse, as it happened in 1995, then both sides must pay close attention to the public response.
Whoever is doomed to lose will have to change course and seek compromise.
This may indeed be an optimistic view.
Particularism and polarization are bigger today than they were in the mid-1990s, and they seem to be a bigger ideological gap between Obama and Congressional Republicans than between President Bill Clinton and Republicans at the time.
At the same time, the activists of both parties see 2010 as a mere prelude to a much more consistent 2012 election.
Thus, the courtesy shown this week may be welcomed by many Americans.
However, it will require much more effort on both sides to find a common denominator in the issues that still separate the two.
