Today, Red Bull’s team employs 180 highly skilled young people using powerful computer systems to analyze and make all kinds of changes to the car.
The Siemens manager explained that the PLM software is able to analyze and improve all components of Red Bull’s racing cars, with the exception of the engine, for which Renault is solely responsible.
The materials, fuel, aerodynamics and safety elements are changed.
The changes can be transferred from the simulator’s virtual reality to reality in less than 24 hours, thanks to advanced production facilities and high-tech autoclaves.
The only limit to this crazy technical perfectionism is the $40 million a Formula 1 team can spend on racing in a season.
Red Bull has built its high-tech factory for the development and manufacture of its racing cars in a location 50 kilometers from London.
These are two buildings where visits, especially by journalists, are severely limited.
Everything that happens is top secret.
The staff consists of 580 people, including the two pilots, world champion Vettel and Mark Webber.
But Red Bull’s true Formula 1 hero is undoubtedly the newest world champion Sebastian Vetell.
Behind the enormous technological resources that the Energy Drink manufacturer puts in the service of its participation on the racing tracks, other protagonists, whose support is invaluable and whose fame is equal to zero, hide.
Steve Nevey, head of technology at the plant, emphasizes that five years ago, progress in R&D for racing cars contributed 50 percent to the victory and the drivers were responsible for the rest.
