How can these processes be understood?
It should be understood that Merkel’s position is not a mistake in her public relations work.
On the contrary, it is a new round in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
Germany is taking a fundamentally new perspective on shaping our future, which collides with the preservation of the ancient traditions of most of its partners.
In the face of the resistance in Europe, Germany is beginning to speculate on three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first: a strong euro with Germany, Austria, the Netherlands and other countries, while the South would have to leave the eurozone.
The second: the reintroduction of the German mark – although it sounds more like science fiction at the moment – is supported by a large proportion of the public opinion, about 50 percent of the population.
This means: more macroeconomic control; strict fiscal management; punishment of countries that breach the regulations; possibly the suspension of payments of some countries, as well as the expansion of the cost of potential adjustment measures to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been out for some time, so there are no excuses now.
First in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission created incentives for deficits and the German government pulled out a constitutional reform to prevent it from starting in 2016.
