Sport and regulation
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos in the game against Ajax show inventiveness, but not the will to bypass a sanction.
The alleged exclusion by two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the November 23 game against Ajax in the Champions League resulted in a lot of ink being poured out on whether it was an unsporting act or not and whether both players should possibly be sanctioned by the UEFA.
As is commonly known, the two players lost time a few minutes before playing (their team had already clearly won) and played several fouls for the referee to show them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid would lead its group, the two players will fulfill the prescribed penalty at the next league game against the Auxerre and thus enter the next game phase without cards.
Finally, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee penalized the club’s coach, José Mourinho, with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
Provoking a yellow card under such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is more common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos – the unwritten but followed rules in this sport.
Part of the debate that has arisen over the case depicted is due to the fact that a team of the Real Madrid football club (who featured nobleness and honour in his anthem and other times punished his players for similar incidents) played the lead role, and to the dramatization by Mourinho, who added an episode more to his long history as a theatrical and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this behavior not explicitly prohibited by the statutes is contrary to the principles of sport, that is, whether these actions constitute a rule of law.
In this case, the damage caused to the sporting spirit should be examined.
The sports spirit defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that was not jeopardized by these actions because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to prevent the offending players from obtaining an unjustified benefit from the opposite.
The paradox of the plot of the players of Real Madrid is that it does not correspond to what we normally understand by misplay or rule error, because the circumvention of the rule was not done secretly to avoid a sanction, but it should be as striking as possible so that it is punished by the referee.
The players waited and joyfully accepted the penalty.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offenders drew from the deliberate fouls.
It should be emphasized here that the rival was neither put in a disadvantage nor were advantages for the game played, because the obvious result of this action was that the own team had to continue playing with fewer players.
It’s also not a useful strategy for the next game because the club will not have those players.
The advantage is obviously that players can start the next game phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
However, this is a long-term, to a certain extent uncertain advantage, as the team may eventually exit.In addition, players with this approach receive a penalty and move into the second card cycle, in which they exit with one card less than in the first cycle due to card accumulation.
It is not clear whether this is really an advantage.
Ultimately, such approaches are not directed against the spirit of sport, which also includes strategic decisions to get the most out of the regulations.
In this case, the players did not want to bypass a penalty (that would actually be a clear case of rule failure), they preferred to choose when to undergo it.
They made a strategic decision without escaping a punishment or escaping it.
Although the boundary between invention and rule environment is blurred, I believe that this is a clear case of invention.
I have the impression that the controversy arose as a result of two factors: because it was about two self-exclusions and because of the type of rule transfer provoked.
The damage caused to the principles of sport by these actions is less ethical than aesthetic.
