The US changes the rules for obtaining a visa
The persons must present themselves with the visa application services before their interview at the consulate; costs will be reduced waiting times.
As of January 10, 2011, the procedures for applying for a visa at the U.S. Embassy and Consulates will change.
In the new procedure, most applicants will have to present themselves with the Visa Application Services (ASCs, the first letters in English) before their interview at the consulate.
The ASC staff will record the applicant’s biometric data, which will be verified by the consulate before the interview.
The new procedure has certain advantages for aspirants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa will decrease, as it is no longer necessary to pay separately for the appointment, the processing of the visa application and the transport service using which the document is issued.
The applicant shall make only one payment covering the three services.
The current price remains unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visas with application (including visas for temporary employees) and $390 for hands and investors.
Those who only want to extend their visa do not need to have an interview at the consulate, they only need to present themselves at the nearest ASC, where they will present their documents and their fingerprints will be taken.
As the biometric data is collected in the ASC, applicants who need a second appointment for the interview at the consulate will stay there less time than before.
Those applying for the visa at the consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer have to pay the service fee of $26.
Additional information on the new visa application procedure can be found at the following website: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
