The discovery could prove the theory that in hostile environments that were previously considered uninhabitable, human-like creatures could exist.The hypothesis was raised that these could transform into intelligent beings – like humans – if their living conditions improved.
It appears to be a microbe found at the bottom of the Mono Lake in Yosemite National Park, California, where she lives in an environment that has been thought to be too poisonous for all imaginable life forms because the lake is highly arsenic.
Somehow, the microbe uses arsenic as a survival resource. Taking this ability into account increases the chances that there might be similar life on other planets that do not have our protective atmosphere.
When these organisms metabolize arsenic, according to the astrobiologists, it is proven that "there is actually a different form of life, a second form of life, different from the one we know."
The space agency will announce the actual range of its fund tomorrow, Thursday, at a press conference.
