Global plan for the renewal of lighting
Yesterday, the UN in Cancun proposed a plan to renew the lighting of households, trade and industry in 100 countries with a view to achieving a reduction in greenhouse gases (GHGs) equivalent to one-third of the additional reduction needed to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan takes its place in the steps of the concrete major projects that the UN hopes to implement in Cancun to compensate for the absence of compulsory reduction commitments by the industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, the main problem in the form of the 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of CFCs released to the earth due to lighting would be avoided if the white-glowing bulbs, which are still a 50-70% monopoly on the market, were replaced by fluorescent or better, LEDs.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This is equivalent to 70% of the emissions of the world’s vehicle fleet.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitters such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans to reduce global CFC emissions from 53 to 49 Gt.
However, 5Gt would have to be deducted from this balance sheet to stabilize the climate rise by 2 degrees Celsius from now until 2020 to prevent it from falling out of control.
In the white-glowing pearls, 95% of the energy escapes in the form of heat, and the remaining 5% produce the light.
With the compact fluorescent bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75%, with the new LED bulbs, this energy requirement is reduced even more than twice.
Compact fluorescent bulbs last an average of 6000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those that the manufacturer Philips launched this week – this company has, by the way, participated in the UN study – have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a white-glowing bulb, giving a hint of the savings opportunities of the replacement plan to be applied in 100 countries.
In addition to the fact that iese completely new bulbs emit very little heat, they can also work with a rule resistance.
They do not contain mercury.
Several specialists have shown that compact fluorescent bulbs have reserves because they contain mercury and must therefore be disposed of as special waste, which is not always possible in developing countries unless the manufacturers provide a reception point.
However, according to the report, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the compact fluorescent bulbs, but rather the coal-fired power plants, which emit significantly more mercury to generate the electricity wasted by the white-glowing bulbs.
In the United States alone, these coal-fired power plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury annually.
The report outlines in detail the gains that each country would generate thanks to this international program.
For example, Indonesia would save $1 billion annually on electricity purchases and eight million tons of CO2, which is equivalent to 3.5 coal-fired power plants, the construction of which would cost Indonesia $2.5 billion.
