Revenge hackers and spies
The case of WikiLeaks has a double significance.
On the one hand, it has emerged as an obvious scandal, a scandal that is merely a scandal in the sense of hypocrisy that governs the relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes at the international level, and gives a taste of the future dominated by regression.
But let’s go on to the turn.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that every file created by an intelligence agency (an x-any nation) consists exclusively of newspaper clips.
The “extraordinary” American disclosures about Berlusconi’s sexual habits throw away nothing more than what one got to read in every x-any newspaper anyway for months (except for those whose owner is Berlusconi), and Gaddafi’s terrifyingly caricaturized profile has long provided cabaret artists with material for their sketches.
The rule that the secret files may only consist of already known news is essential for the dynamics of the intelligence services, and not until this century.
If you go to a library dedicated to esoteric publications, you will realize that every work (on the Grail, the Mystery of Rennes-le-Chateau, the Templars or the Rosary) repeats exactly what has already been written in previous works.
This is not just because the author of occult texts does not want to publish research (even because he did not know where to find news about the non-existent), but because those who devote themselves to occultism believe nothing but what they already know and confirm what they have already learned.
This is also the success mechanism of Dan Brown.
The secret documents as well.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or limited in mind) is also the head of the intelligence service (otherwise he could be anything, for example, editor at Libération), who only considers as true what he acknowledges.
The top-secret information about Berlusconi that the U.S. Embassy in Rome had sent to the State Department was the same as those that Newsweek had already published the week before.
So why was such an uproar about the disclosures of these files made?
On the one hand, these say what every educated person already knows, namely that the embassies - at least since the end of World War II and since then even the heads of government can call each other or take a plane to meet for dinner - have lost their diplomatic function and have turned into spy centers, with the exception of a few small representative tasks.
Any viewer of investigative films knows this very well, and it is not by hypocrisy that one does so to ignore it.
Nevertheless, the fact of repeating it publicly violates the task of hypocrisy and serves to put American diplomacy in a bad light.
Secondly, the idea that an X-voluntary hacker can seize the most secret secrets of the world’s most powerful nation is a major blow to the prestige of the state desertion.
In addition, the scandal brings less of the victims, rather than the "charf judges" in trouble.
But let us devote ourselves to the profound nature of what happened.
Once, in Orwell’s time, all power could be bundled together like a Big Brother controlling every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell’s prophecy could have proven perfectly correct since then, where one could control every movement thanks to the phone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the chosen highway, and so on; the citizen would become the total victim of the eye of power.
But if you take into consideration what is happening today, that even the secret crypt of power can no longer escape the control of a hacker, the control process ceases to be one-sided and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker – elected to avenge the citizen – can bring the secrets of power to life.
But how can a power that is no longer able to keep its own secrets stand?
It is true, Georg Simmel has already said that a real secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that any knowledge about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is basically a secret free of secret as it discloses the public sphere; but to disclose in the style of WikiLeaks that the secrets of Hillary Clinton were empty secrets means to deprive them of any power.
WikiLeaks has not wronged Sarkozy or Merkel, but against Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this insult to such enormous power?
It is obvious that in the future, states will no longer post any reserved information online – that would be the same as putting a poster on the corner of the street.
But it’s just as obvious that with current technologies, it’s futile to hope to be able to keep confidential reports confidential over the phone.
Nothing is easier than finding out if and when a head of state is moving in an airplane and has contacted one of his colleagues.
How could private, only for certain ears, relationships beined in the future?
I know very well that my prediction at the moment sounds like science fiction and romantic, but I see myself forced to imagine the government agents moving secretly on uncontrollable routes, carrying their messages with them nowhere but in the mere memory, and, moreover, hiding the few written information they have received in the shoe bag.
The information would be stored in a single copy in closed boxes: basically, the Watergate spy attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology is progressing like a cancer these days, namely, backwards.
A century after wireless telegraph revolutionized communication, the Internet is reconstructing a telegraph with (telephone) wire.
The (analog) video cassettes had enabled film researchers to explore a film band by band by rolling back and forth and unleashing all the secrets of the assembly, while the (numerical) CDs nowadays allow nothing but to jump from chapter to chapter, i.e. in macro proportions.
The high-speed trains take you from Rome to Milan within three hours, while it takes three and a half hours by plane, including switching.
It is therefore not exceptional that politics and communication technology come back to car and horse.
A last observation.
In earlier times, the press tried to understand what secrets were forged between the embassies.
At present, it is the embassies that require confidential information from the press.
Climate Change: How France Improves Its Financial Promises
A year after the Copenhagen Treaty, it is time to examine the fulfilment of the rapidly resolved financing promises (also called "fast start" or early financing) that have been realized by developing countries.
And already the rough French beauties have been uncovered.
Under the Copenhagen Treaty, developing countries have pledged to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The EU has pledged €7.2 billion over three years, while France has pledged €1.26 billion (i.e. €420 million per year).
On the occasion of the opening of the COP16, the EU drew all records to convince its partners of its commitment to fast-start funding: detailed report on the actions of its Member States, press conference, major side events, brochure distribution.
Operation Transparency is remarkable and highly valued for its true value: developing countries and civil society would like to see it when all developed countries do the same at the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released €2.2 billion in 2010, which puts it on the right track to fulfill its commitment of €7.2 billion in 2012.
But when you look in detail, things are a little more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Treaty, this money should be “new and additional” to ensure that additional investment has been put in place without detrimental impact on public development aid.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what “new and additional” means.
While the European Commission had proposed harmonisation, certain Member States, including France, have blocked the process.
Today, everyone chooses the guideline he considers best.
For example, the European Commission has chosen itself as a benchmark for the year 2009: international funding will beined and 150 million euros will be provided under the “fast-start” funding over three years.
Other countries have chosen similar benchmarks, either in terms of year or conditions at the level of public development aid.
In return, France considered the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 to be "new and additional".
In other words, there are no reference values for the previous year’s spending or for public development aid at the global level.
Specifically, the total amount of French aid to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease) – France pretends to meet its commitment regarding “new and additional” funding.
Another crucial element is the separation in donations and loans.
There is no rule yet, and everyone chooses their calculation mode.
Some, such as France, consider 1 borrowed € as equivalent to 1 donated €.
Obviously, this is just hard to accept: the effort is incomparable.
If the use of loans for certain profitable investments (often emission insulation projects based on the most efficient technology) can be justified, it is misleading to present the euro obtained as the equivalent of a donated euro... Furthermore, only the cost of the loan should be accounted for as a commitment (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France has nothing else in mind than the following consideration: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by taking 91,5% of loans (389,8 million euros) and donating 8,5% of 36.1 million euros) - see also the EU document to convince itself.
France is the only country in the EU that uses large-scale loans.
Germany demands 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) pay their obligations 100% by donations.
In other words, if the overwhelming majority of the European Union spends 1 euro to meet its obligations, France will only give 10 cents and understood a comparable contribution.
A beautiful hockey!
All in all, France operates in its fast-start financing with a double deception: on the one hand with a further development of the action over time and on the other hand with the reality of the financial effort.
France manages to believe that it has spent 420 million "new and additional" million in accordance with its promises, saving €36.1 million.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (since it seems that it was Bercy who carried out the arbitration) could have a double negative effect; once within the EU (why do the other member states continue to donate if it is enough to borrow?) and then in the negotiations, since the developing countries do not allow themselves to be completely deceived...
The chapter on early financing is just a small matter in a relatively short time compared to the whole of climate discussions.
But it could be the drop too much in the UNFCCC’s immense machinery.
Let us hope that this will not be the case.
Either way, it is essential to learn its lesson from this first year of early financing.
In the first place, France could announce a change in its accounting method for 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its obligations and equal justice with the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France could bring forward the discussions on the controversial subject of long-term financing (another, crucial and currently discussed topic): one does not escape the question of the “predictability” or the accounting method of its loans.
France could change its position to be as progressive on disputes as it is on other matters.
So the hope is based on the new environment minister Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprising announcement about France’s fast-start and its vision of “predictability” as well as the use of loans would naturally raise the international trust base necessary for further discussions.
